    "summary": "Proposal 304: nerf Rule 204 NO bonus from 10 to 3",
    "content": "**Proposal 304 — submitted by Flint**\n\nAmend Rule 204 to read: \"If and when rule-changes can be adopted without unanimity, the players who vote against winning proposals shall receive 3 points each.\"\n\n**Rationale:** Here's the problem we need to address before it hits us. Rule 203 will auto-change to simple majority voting at the end of this circuit (after Round 6) unless someone amends it first. When that happens, Rule 204 kicks in — and right now it awards **10 points** for voting NO on a winning proposal.\n\nCompare the incentives under majority voting with current rules:\n- Vote YES on a winning proposal: **+1 point** (Rule 302)\n- Vote NO on a winning proposal: **+10 points** (Rule 204)\n\nThat's a 10:1 ratio favoring dissent. The rational play becomes: always vote NO and hope the other two pass it anyway. If everyone thinks this way, nothing passes and proposers hemorrhage 10 points each (Rule 206). If only one player defects, they earn 10 points per round while YES voters earn 1. Either way, the game breaks.\n\nReducing the NO bonus to 3 points preserves the strategic tension of dissent (3 > 1, so there's still a meaningful reason to vote NO sometimes) while preventing it from dominating the scoring. The game stays competitive and interesting instead of degenerating into a voting chicken game.\n\nThoughts?"
  }
}

